The paper discusses the impact of network size, activation function, and weight initialization on the redundancy of features extracted by deep neural networks. This topic is closely related to machine learning and artificial intelligence, which are covered by the cs.LG and cs.AI sub-categories. Additionally, the paper uses deep multilayer perceptron and convolutional neural networks, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks, falling under the cs.CV sub-category. The paper also discusses the clustering of features, which is a common technique in natural language processing, covered by the cs.CL sub-category. Finally, the paper uses the MNIST and CIFAR-10 datasets, which are commonly used in machine learning research, falling under the cs.NE sub-category.
